info.description:
# NanamiLang - Chiaki Nanami Programming Language (just kidding) ## Key points Visit [ReadTheDocs](https://nanamilang.readthedocs.io/en/latest/) to read Nanamilang documentation. 1. The project main goal is to create a LISP language dialect with immutable data structures. 2. The project name was inspired by the character Chiaki Nanami from the game named Danganronpa v2. ## Data types ### Simple data types | Type Name | Purpose | |-----------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------| | *Nil* | To mark as a nil | | *Boolean* | Encapsulate Python 3 bool | | *String* | Encapsulate Python 3 str | | *Date* | Encapsulate Python 3 datetime.datetime class | | *FloatNumber* | Encapsulate Python 3 float | | *IntegerNumber* | Encapsulate Python 3 int | | *Keyword* | Encapsulate Python 3 str | | *NException* | Encapsulate Python 3 Exception class | | *Undefined* | To mark as an undefined at parse-time | | *Macro* | Encapsulate macro name and its Python 3 handle | | *Function* | Encapsulate function name and its Python 3 handle | | *Symbol* | Encapsulate Python 3 str | ### Complex data types | Type Name | Purpose | |-----------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------| | *Vector* | Implements a Vector of NanamiLang Base data types | | *HashSet* | Implements a HashSet of NanamiLang Base data types | | *HashMap* | Implements a HashMap of NanamiLang Base data types | ## People involved in the project 1. @jedi2light - (aka. Stoian Minaiev) - creator & maintainer of the project. 2. @buzzer13 - the project contains `AST._create()` method implementation initially proposed by that person. ## Project installation & proposed ways to use 1. There are two ways to get Nanamilang installed on your system: 1. `$ pip3 install [--user] nanamilang` (requires `Pip3`, maybe easiest way to install) 2. `$ git clone nanamilang && cd nanamilang && make build && make install` (requires `GNU Make`) 1. `` could be on of the proposed: 1. 2. 3. 2. Check whether your `~/.local/bin` and `~/.local/lib` directories are present in your `$PATH` environment variable. 3. `nanamilang-repl.py` starts an interactive REPL environment, where you can play around with Nanamilang. 4. `nanamilang-frmt.py` reads a source code from file (if it exists), tokenizes it, produces a formatted string. 5. `nanamilang-eval.py` reads a source code from file (if it exists), evaluates it, returns a value to a host system. ### NanamiLang evaluator script options explained 1. `` First argument, must be a path to the source code of your Nanamilang program. You can omit that. 2. `--lisence` It just tells the script to show NanamiLang core license. Output would be `License is GNU GPL v2` 3. `--version` It just tells the script to show Nanamilang core version. Output would be `NanamiLang ..

` 4. `--include-traceback` It tells the REPL script to show you a traceback of occurred exception. Technically, its just tells `nanamilang.datatypes/NException.format(include_traceback=True)` to include tb. ### NanamiLang formatter script options explained 1. `` First argument, must be a path to the source code of your Nanamilang program. You can omit that. 2. `--lisence` It just tells the script to show NanamiLang core license. Output would be `License is GNU GPL v2` 3. `--version` It just tells the script to show Nanamilang core version. Output would be `NanamiLang ..

` ### NanamiLang interactive REPL script options explained 1. `--no-greeting` It tells the REPL script to not show you certain information like: `readline` history path, 'how to get doc' and 'how to exit from REPL' tips once the REPL has been started. 2. `--include-traceback` It tells the REPL script to show you a traceback of occurred exception. Technically, its just tells `nanamilang.datatypes/NException.format(include_traceback=True)` to include tb. 3. `--show-measurements` You can measure evaluation time using `(measure ...)` macro (see also `(doc measure)` to get more). But `--show-measurements` tells the REPL script to show `nanamilang.program.Program.mesaurements()` for each stage of `nanamilang.program.Program`, including: `Tokenizer.tokenize()`, `AST._create()`, `AST.evaluate()`. ### NanamiLang Core API usage example in Python (CPython) 3 ```python3 from nanamilang import program source: str = str('(+ 2 2 (* 2 2))') program: program.Program = program.Program(source) program.format() # => "(+ 2 2 (* 2 2))" program.ast() # => get encapsulated AST instance program.tokenized() # => collection of a Token instances results = program.evaluate() # => ((: 8, ...),) ``` ## License **NanamiLang is licensed under GNU GPL version 2, was initially made by @jedi2light (aka Stoian Minaiev), October 2021**
